1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ga8a7,Gb7b5,Gc8f5]
This little move is the introduction into Chebanenco Slav. As beginners, we
are taught to develop our pieces and pawns towards the center as quickly as
possible. So how does one justify playing with a marginal pawn on move 4? The
basic explanation lies in the fact that black would like to develop his
light-squared bishop to f5, but he can not do it so easily due to the weakness
of b7 pawn. In the variation 4...Bf5 5.cxd5 followed by 6.Qb3! black runs into
difficulties defending that pawn.  We have seen that in the Semi-Slav black
abandons the Bf5 idea altogether by playing 4...e6. In the Classical Slav, he
solves this problem by taking on c4 first and getting the bishop out
afterwards. This, however gives up the control of central square e4, which
takes away a small amount of solidity that black is counting on in the Slav
defense. Having said all that, there is a way to keep the central pawn
structure intact AND play Bf5/Bg4 - and that is the Chebanenco Slav, beginning
with 4...a6.   How exactly does black address the problem of b7 pawn with this
move? Well, in two ways. Firstly, a6 enables black to defend actively with
b7-b5 in certain variations. And secondly, he can defend it in a more quiet
and unusual manner with Ra7!? We will see examples of both throughout the
chapters. It should also be said that a6 may be a generally useful move in the
Slav, especially in connection to dxc4 and b7-b5 idea.} (4... Bf5 $6 5. cxd5 {
[%csl Rb7,Rd5][%cal Gd1b3]}) (4... e6 {[%csl Rc8]}) (4... dxc4 {[%csl Re4]
[%cal Ge2e4]}) {In response to the Chebanenco, white has many options. The
most principled one seems to be 5.c5 since with a6 black has weakened his
control over b6 square. Yet, I have never been a huge fan of this blocking
move as I believe white should keep central flexibility. Objectively speaking,
though, this move is probably on par with the one that I suggest for our
repertoire:} 5. e3 {This is a simple developing scheme similar to what we do
against the Semi-Slav. White is not convinced that by playing a7-a6, black has
fully solved his issues with b7 pawn, as we will see in CHAPTERS 1 and 2.} ({
The most common alternatives are:} 5. c5 {[%csl Rb6]}) (5. a4 {[%cal Rb7b5]}) (
5. cxd5) (5. Ne5 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ge5c4]}) (5. g3) (5. Bg5) 5... b5 {[%csl Rc5,
Rc6] This move stops white's Qb3 ideas for good. However, it is also
potentially weaknening the queenside, especially c6 and c5 squares, and we
will see later how white can exploit that in some positions.} ({The second
most common move here is} 5... e6 {which transposes into the Semi-slav with 5..
.a6, which we have covered in the Repertoire against the Semi-Slav, CHAPTER 1.}
) ({A very popular variation as of late is} 5... Bf5 {[%csl Gf5] where I
suggest the principled response} 6. Qb3 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gb3b7] after which
black has two ways to defend the b7 pawn:} {1)} Ra7 ({and 2)} 6... b5 7. cxd5
cxd5 8. a4 b4 $1 9. Qxb4 Nc6 10. Qc5 Na5 11. Bxa6 $1 Rxa6 12. Qb5+ Rc6 13. Ne5
{covered in CHAPTER 1}) 7. Nh4 {covered in CHAPTER 2}) ({There are also a few
minor alternatives, such as Kamsky's} 5... g6) ({and} 5... Bg4 6. Qb3 Ra7 7.
Ne5 {which will be dealt with in CHAPTER 3.}) {Similarly to the previous
junction, white can remain flexible with} 6. b3 ({or close the game with} 6. c5
{Again, I prefer flexibility.}) 6... Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1] Developing the bishop
with the pin is the most natural continuation.} ({The alternative covered in
CHAPTER 4 is} 6... Bf5 {and here instead of the more common 7.Bd3, I suggest a
more aggresive approach:} 7. Ne5 {[%cal Gg2g4]} h6 {[%cal Gf5h7]} (7... e6 8.
g4 {[%csl Rf5]}) 8. Bd3 Bxd3 {where I explore an interesting new idea} 9. Nxd3
$5 $146) 7. Be2 {White's development may seem innocuous for now, but things
will get interesting very soon.} e6 {This standard developing move is the most
common.} ({Black can also play} 7... Nbd7 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd7e5] fighting for
the control over e5 square. Here we begin harrassing the light-squared bishop:}
8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 $1 Bg6 10. Ne5 {[%csl Rg6]} Nxe5 11. dxe5 {and the play
suddenly becomes very sharp. This important position is explored in CHAPTER 5.}
) 8. h3 Bh5 {Principled, though black is not obliged to go to h5.} ({He can
also swap the bishop for knight} 8... Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Nbd7 10. O-O {when we reach
a typical Slav position where the bishop pair guarantees a slightly more
promising future for white than for black. I explain how to play in this type
of position in CHAPTER 6.}) ({If black goes to} 8... Bf5 {then white can still
pursue the bishop with} 9. g4 {\/when the best solution is nevertheless} Bg6 {
so we transpose into the 8...Bh5 line.}) 9. g4 $1 {[%csl Rh5] More critical
than 9.0-0. This chasing maneuvre is quite normal in the Slav defense and
sometimes the only way for white to disturb the balance that black is trying
to achieve.} (9. O-O {leads to a more positional game. Black seems to be doing
fine after:} Nbd7 10. Bb2 Bd6 11. Ne5 Bxe2 12. Nxe2 bxc4 $1 13. bxc4 O-O) 9...
Bg6 10. Ne5 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh3h4] White wants to pursue black bishop with
h4-h5, using the fact that black can not really move his h-pawn due to Nxg6
fxg6, which is a horrible pawn structure for black. Here black has several
ways to counter white's plan. The most solid one is} Nfd7 ({In CHAPTER 7, we
investigate a sharp alternative} 10... Bb4 11. Bd2 Bxc3 12. Bxc3 Ne4 13. Rc1) (
{as well as less critical moves, such as} 10... Ne4) ({and} 10... bxc4) 11.
Nxg6 hxg6 {[%csl Rb8,Gc1,Rc6,Re1,Ge2][%cal Gh8h1] and we reach probably the
most important position of this line. White's advantage is still not clear as
black is without major weaknesses. We will explore this position in depth in
CHAPTER 8, with an emphasis on a rare plan Kf1!?-Kg2, which seems to be the
right path to get the advantage for white.} *

