1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. e3 Bf5 6. Qb3 {[%csl Rb7] As
annunced in the introduction, white wants to exploit the weakness of b7 pawn
whenever possible.} ({Alternatives for more positionally inclined are} 6. Bd3)
({or its cousin} 6. Be2 h6 7. Bd3 $5 {invented by Magnus Carlsen himself.}) ({
Another ambitious try is} 6. Ne5) ({while} 6. Nh4 {is perhaps premature in the
absence of e6, although playable as well.}) {Black has two ways to defend the
pawn: 1)} 6... b5 ({and 2)} 6... Ra7 $5 {which we will cover in the next
chapter.}) 7. cxd5 {We continue in the straightforward fashion, trying to make
use white's extra tempo in the opening. From now on, there is no turning back
and in his pursuit of advantage, white needs to be ready to make long-term
sacrifices!} (7. c5 {is a good alternative, but it leads to a completely
different type of game.}) 7... cxd5 8. a4 b4 $1 {This pawn sacrifice is the
point of Black's defense with 6...b5.} ({Other moves are barely playable: 1)} 
8... bxa4 {[%csl Ra6,Rb7]} 9. Qb7 $1 {Taking on a4 is fine, but white can be
even more aggresive.} Nbd7 {White would usually take on a4 and later pick up
the a6 pawn as well; however he can push the envelope with} 10. Ne5 $1 $146
Nxe5 11. dxe5 Ne4 12. Nxd5 Rc8 13. Bxa6 Nc5 14. Bb5+ Bd7 15. Bxd7+ Qxd7 16.
Qxd7+ Nxd7 17. Bd2 $16 {[%csl Gb2] leaving him with a healthy extra pawn in
the endgame.}) ({2)} 8... Qa5 $2 {is poor due to} 9. Bd2 b4 10. Na2 {and black
loses the pawn without compensation.}) 9. Qxb4 Nc6 10. Qc5 {The most active
and principled response.} Na5 {Played unanimously, though alternatives exist.}
({Black never tested an interesting idea: 2)} 10... Bd7 $5 $146 {threatening
to trap the queen with e6/e5. Now white's best move is} 11. Ne5 $1 ({He should
not be greedy with} 11. Nxd5 $6 e5 12. Qc4 {because Black develops serious
counterplay after} Rc8 $1 13. Nxf6+ gxf6 14. Qb3 e4 $1 $36 {and despite two
extra pawns white will be in trouble after Be6 and Nb4.}) 11... e6 12. Nxc6 Qc7
13. Ne7 $1 {A rarely seen idea. White is better in all cases: 1)} Qb8 ({2)} 
13... Qxc5 14. dxc5 Bxe7 15. b4 a5 16. bxa5 ({White can also claim advantage
after creating a defended passed pawn:} 16. b5 Bxc5 17. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Ga4,Gb5]
}) 16... Rxa5 17. Bd2 Rxc5 18. a5 {[%csl Ga5]} Bd6 19. Bd3 Ke7 20. Ke2 $14) ({
3)} 13... Qb7 14. a5 $1 Bxe7 15. Qb6 $14 {using the fact that Black queen is
undefended.}) 14. Qa3 Bxe7 15. Qa2 O-O {Black apparently has compensation, but
white should gradually develop all his pieces and prove the advantage:} 16. Bd3
Bd6 (16... e5 17. O-O Be6 18. h3 $14) 17. h3 Rc8 18. O-O Qb7 19. Bd2 e5 20. b4
$1 exd4 21. exd4 Bxb4 22. Rfb1 a5 23. Ne2 $14 {[%csl Rb4]}) ({3) Another idea
to trap the queen is} 10... Nb8 {though now white has} 11. a5 $1 {[%cal Gc5b6]}
e6 12. Qb6 Qc8 13. Qb3 Nc6 14. Qa4 $14) 11. Bxa6 $1 {An excellent resource in
fight for initiative. White will now be down on material, but ahead in
development.} Rxa6 12. Qb5+ Rc6 13. Ne5 {[%csl Ra5,Rc6,Re8]} Bd7 (13... Qa8 $2
{allows} 14. e4 $1 Bxe4 (14... Nxe4 15. Nxd5 $18) (14... dxe4 15. d5 $18) 15.
b4 $18) 14. Nxd7 Nxd7 {Much more natural} ({than} 14... Kxd7 {Here White needs
to continue in sacrificial mode rather than take the material:} 15. e4 $1 {
[%csl Rd7][%cal Gc1g5]} (15. Nxd5 {0-1 Kanter,E (2406)-Bogner,S (2587)/Dubai
2014/CBM 159 Extra (33)} Nxd5 16. Qxd5+ Kc8 17. Qxf7 e6 18. O-O Nb3 19. Rb1 Qc7
$17) 15... e6 16. Bg5 $36 {[%csl Rd5] and white developed a strong attack in
the following correspodence game:} Nc4 17. exd5 exd5 18. O-O Nd6 $2 {A poor
choice.} ({The alternatives were more stubborn 1)} 18... Qa5 19. Rfc1 $1 {
[%cal Gb2b3]} Qxb5 20. axb5 Rb6 21. Ra7+ Ke6 22. Bxf6 gxf6 23. g4 $1 {[%csl
Re6]} Kd6 24. Re1 h5 25. Re8 hxg4 26. Raa8 $16) ({2)} 18... Qb6 19. Rfc1 Nxb2
20. Bxf6 Qxb5 21. axb5 Rxf6 22. Nxd5 Rd6 23. Rc7+ Ke6 24. Nf4+ Kf5 25. g3 $40 {
[%csl Rf5]}) 19. Qd3 Nde4 20. Nxe4 dxe4 21. Qb5 Qb6 22. Qf5+ Kc7 23. d5 Qa5 24.
Bxf6 Rxf6 25. d6+ $1 Kb6 26. Qc8 $18 {1-0 Bars,J-Salonen,J (2049)/ICCF email
2010/Corr 2013 (49)}) 15. Bd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2a5,Ga1c1] Again, the most active
move, looking to bring both the bishop and the rook into the game.} ({
Materialistic} 15. Nxd5 $6 {was punished in the following game:} e6 16. Bd2
exd5 17. Bxa5 Qa8 18. O-O Rc8 19. Bc3 Rb8 20. Qe2 Bb4 {[%csl Ra4,Rb2,Gb4,Gd5,
Re3] White's pawns are blocked and, as such, of little value to him.} 21. Qg4
g6 22. a5 f5 23. Qf4 Bxc3 24. bxc3 O-O 25. Qd6 Rf7 $15 {0-1 Kantans,T (2343)
-Kireev,A (2355)/Pardubice 2010/CBM 137 Extra (30)}) {Black is at an important
crossroads.} 15... Rc8 {is the most popular move, chosen by Vallejo in one of
the first outings of this variation.} ({1)} 15... Qa8 {is the alternative.
Just a few months back, Viktor Bologan (one of the main proponents of
