is one of the most critical games in the line:} 16. Nxd5 e6 17. Nf4 $1 {[%csl
Ra5,Ra8,Rc6,Re8] Again, avoiding simplification and playing for initiative.
Black pieces are clumsy and he will need a few extra moves to get organized.
In the meantime, white can prepare a serious offensive.} (17. Bxa5 $6 exd5 {
-15.Nxd5}) 17... Ra6 (17... Nc4 18. Rc1 Qc8 19. b3 Nce5 20. O-O $1 $18) 18. O-O
Bd6 (18... Nb7 19. a5 Nd6 20. Qa4 $36 {[%cal Gf4d3]}) 19. d5 $1 exd5 20. Rfd1 {
[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd2c3,Gd1d5] This strong idea was obviously prepared by
Jakovenko at home.} Nc6 ({It seemed safer to try and prevent Bc3 with} 20... d4
$142 {though white can still keep the initiative with, for example:} 21. Bb4
Bxb4 22. Qxb4 Nc6 23. Qa3 $36) 21. Bc3 ({Another strong possibility is} 21.
Qxd5 $5 Ne7 22. Qxa8+ Rxa8 23. a5 $36 {[%csl Ga5,Gb2][%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5]
followed by very unpleasant b4-b5 etc.}) 21... Bxf4 (21... O-O 22. Rxd5 {does
not change much.}) 22. exf4 O-O 23. Rxd5 {[%csl Gb5,Gc3,Gd5]} Nb6 $2 {A
blunder by Bologan.} ({He absolutely had to play} 23... Nf6 {after which his
position looks holdable} 24. Bxf6 gxf6 25. Rd3 $44) 24. Rg5 g6 {[%csl Rg8]
[%cal Gc3h8] A sad neccessity.} ({Bologan missed that after the planned} 24...
f6 {White has a great shot} 25. Rxg7+ $1 Kxg7 26. Qg5+ Kh8 ({or} 26... Kf7 27.
Qxf6+ Ke8 28. Re1+ Kd7 29. Qg7+ Kc8 30. Qxf8+ $18) 27. Bxf6+ Rxf6 28. Qxf6+ Kg8
{and now the decisive move is} 29. Ra3 $1 $18 {[%cal Ga3g3]}) 25. a5 Rd8 26.
Re1 Nc8 27. Rd5 Rxd5 $4 {[%csl Ge8,Rg8] A huge blunder, though the position
was lost either way.} 28. Re8# {1-0 Jakovenko,D (2737)-Bologan,V (2654)/Doha
QAT 2015}) ({2) Black hasn't got time to develop} 15... e6 {because he loses
material after the simple} 16. Ne2 {[%csl Ra5,Rc6][%cal Gd2a5]}) 16. Nxd5 Nc4 (
16... Nc6 {is just too passive.} 17. O-O e6 18. Rac1 $1 Na7 19. Qa6 exd5 20.
Ba5 $1 Nb8 21. Qxa7 Qd7 22. Rxc8+ Qxc8 23. Bd2 {followed by Rc1 and march of
the a-pawn looks very grim for the undeveloped Black side.}) 17. Rc1 ({Slow} 
17. Bb4 $6 {was tested in a few games, but with accurate play Black takes over
the initiative!} e6 18. Bxf8 exd5 $1 19. Bc5 {1-0 Stryjecki,M (2441)-Jirka,J 
(2292)/Patras 2001/CBM 083 Extra (69)'} (19. Bxg7 Rg8 20. Bh6 Qe7 $1 $19) 19...
Qc7 20. a5 Rb8 21. Qa4 Nxb2 $19) 17... Nd6 ({It goes without saying that black
can not afford to develop another white piece:} 17... Nxd2 $2 18. Kxd2 {[%cal
Gh1c1]} e6 19. Rxc8 Qxc8 20. Rc1 $18) 18. Rxc8 Qxc8 19. Qa6 $3 {The key idea.
By exchanging queens, white will increase the power of his passed pawns.} (19.
Qa5 {is enough for draw only, after} Nc4 20. Nc7+ ({White was too ambitious
with} 20. Qa7 e6 21. Nc7+ Kd8 22. Nb5 Bd6 23. Nxd6 Nxd6 24. O-O Ke7 25. Qa5 f5
26. Rc1 Qb7 $17 {and got punished in 0-1 Tregubov,P (2628)-Vallejo Pons,F 
