Qxa6 ({An equivalent alternative is} 19... e6 20. Qxc8+ Nxc8 21. Nc7+ {White
needs to play for every tempo even in the endgame.} (21. Nf4 {[%cal Gb2b4,
Ga4a5,Gf4d3,Ge1e2] looks good at first, but black gets just enough time to
re-organize with} Bd6 22. Nd3 Ncb6 23. b3 e5 $132) 21... Kd8 22. Na6 Ncb6 23.
a5 Nc4 24. b4 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4,Gd4,Rd8,Rf8,Rh8]} Kc8 {This position was reached
in a correspodence game and here we have an important improvement:} 25. Ke2 $1
$146 {[%cal Gh1c1]} ({In the game, white played} 25. Nc5 $6 {too early and
found his pawns blocked after} Bxc5 26. dxc5 Nf6 27. Ke2 Kc7 28. Bc3 Kc6 29.
Ra1 Kb5 $17 {0-1 Ward,R (2233)-Gertners,G (2271)/ICCF email 2007/Corr 2013 (47)
}) 25... Kb7 26. Rc1 Kxa6 ({Now the key idea is} 26... Nxd2 27. b5 $3 {[%cal
Gc1c7]} Bd6 28. Kxd2 $16) 27. Rxc4 Be7 28. Rc7 Rd8 29. e4 $14 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4,
Gd4,Rd7,Rd8,Ge4,Re7] Black is in a very passive position, which gives white
good chances to press for full point.}) 20. Nc7+ Kd8 21. Nxa6 {[%csl Ga4,Gb2,
Rd8,Rf8,Rh8] We reached an important position which requires detailed analysis.
Conceptually, white's lead in development and two passed pawns on the
queenside should provide him with enough compensation for the piece, if not
more. However, concrete variations are needed to support this evaluation. In
some ways, this endgame is similar to sharp Sicilian endgames when white
sacrifices a piece on b5 in order to obtain three connected passed queenside
pawns.  As far as practical material goes, only one tournament game has been
played from this position. Though white won relatively easily, black could
have defended better.} Nc4 {It is very questionable whether black needs to
waste an important tempo attacking this bishop.} ({Possibly the best
continuation is} 21... e5 $5 22. Ke2 exd4 23. exd4 $14 {[%cal Ge2d3,Gb2b4,
Ga6c5,Ga4a5] Here white has a very simple scheme: put king on d3, push pawns
to a5 and b4, and bring knight to c5.} Ne4 (23... Nc4 24. Bc3 $14 {[%cal Ge2d3]
the knight is unstable on c4.}) 24. Be3 Bd6 25. Kd3 Re8 26. a5 $1 $14 {[%cal
Gb2b4,Ga6c5] Precision is important} (26. b4 $6 {allows the blockade:} Nb6 $1
27. a5 Nd5 $132) {The other route to d5} 26... Ndf6 {doesn't work due to} 27.
f3 $18) (21... e6 {looks pretty logical too} 22. Ke2 Ne4 {Here white has an
extra possibilty to play for initiative:} 23. Ba5+ $1 Kc8 24. Rc1+ Kb7 25. b4
$1 Kxa6 (25... Bd6 26. b5 Rc8 27. Rxc8 Kxc8 28. f3 Nef6 29. g3 $16 {[%cal
Ge3e4,Ge2d3]}) 26. Rc6+ Kb7 27. Rc7+ Ka6 28. Rxd7 Nc3+ (28... f5 29. Rd8 $1
Nc3+ 30. Kd3 Nxa4 31. Bc7 $18) 29. Kd3 Nxa4 30. Rxf7 $16 {[%csl Re6,Rg7] and
white has spreaded his sphere of influence to the kingside.}) (21... Kc8 22. b4
Kb7 {is another slow plan that plays into white's hands:} 23. Nc5+ Nxc5 24.
dxc5 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,Gc5] Achieving this pawn structure is usually a dream come
true for white in this endgame.} Ne4 25. f3 Nxd2 26. Kxd2 $16 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,
Gc5] with something very similar to our main game.  These lines do not exhaust
analytical potential of this position. It is quite possible that improvements
can be found for both sides somewhere along the way. However, based on this
analysis, the general outlook for White is positive if he plays precisely and
knows what he wants to achieve.}) 22. b3 $1 {White does not need to hold onto
this bishop as it is not clear what it's role is.} ({Indeed} 22. Bc3 {proves
to be too slow and it gives black just enough time to consolidate with} Kc8 23.
Ke2 (23. b4 Ndb6 24. a5 Nd5 25. Ke2 Kb7 $132) 23... Ncb6 24. a5 Nd5 25. Bd2 Kb7
26. Nc5+ Nxc5 27. dxc5 e5 $132 {[%cal Gb7c6,Gc6b5]}) 22... Nxd2 23. Kxd2 e6 (
23... e5 {is possibly slightly better as it at least opens up the e-file for
counterplay. Nevertheless, white is on top following his usual plan:} 24. b4
exd4 25. exd4 {[%cal Ge8e1]} Bd6 (25... h5 $5 26. a5 Rh6 27. Nc5 $16) 26. Kd3
Kc8 (26... Re8 27. b5 Nb8 28. Nc5 Nd7 29. Ne4 Bc7 30. Rc1 $16) 27. Rc1+ Kb7 28.
Nc5+ Nxc5+ 29. dxc5 $16 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,Gc5]}) 24. b4 Bd6 25. a5 Kc8 26. Kc3 Kb7
27. Nc5+ $1 $16 {White is firmly in control here and she went on to win the
