1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. e3 Bf5 6. Qb3 Ra7 {[%csl Ra7,Gb7,Gc6,
Gd5] An interesting way of defending the pawn. Black does not weaken his pawn
structure (as in CHAPTER 1) at the expense of misplacing his rook slightly.} 7.
Nh4 {This move has picked up in popularity lately. White is trying to force
black bishop to a less favorable square or else swap his knight for it.} ({In
his excellent book on 1.d4 repertoire for White, Avrukh recommended another
logical plan:} 7. a4 e6 8. a5 {[%cal Gb3b6]} Nbd7 9. Nh4 {However, he slightly
underestimated the following idea:} Be4 $5 10. f3 (10. cxd5 cxd5 $1 $11) 10...
dxc4 $1 (10... Bg6 {is given as the main line, but it is obviously not the
critical try as such positions are usually slightly favorable for white.}) 11.
Bxc4 Bd5 12. g3 {Avrukh assessed this position as slightly better for white,
but in fact black can equalize by force with} Bxc4 {(Improving on the recent
game: 1-0 Pranavananda,V (2115)-Sardana,R (2404)/New Delhi 2015/CBM 164 Extra 
(69))} 13. Qxc4 c5 $1 14. O-O b5 15. axb6 Nxb6 16. Qe2 cxd4 17. exd4 Be7 $11 {
[%csl Rc1,Rd4,Rf3,Rh4]}) 7... Bc8 $5 {A relatively rare, but the most testing
move in this position. Black's development might seem ridicoulous, but his
position is still quite solid and white knight does not look particularly
happy on h4, meaning that white will probably have to waste another tempo on
Nh4-f3.} ({The most common response is} 7... Bg6 8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. g3 e6 {[%csl
Gc1,Gf1] with a typical solid Slav position where white can claim a small plus
thanks to the long-term potential of bishop pair and space advantage.} 10. Bg2
Nbd7 (10... Be7 11. Bd2 Nbd7 12. Ne2 O-O 13. Qc2 Ra8 14. O-O Rc8 15. Rac1 Re8
16. Rfd1 $14 {a long maneuvering game ensued in 1/2-1/2 So,W (2775)-Lin Chen 
(2532)/Doha QAT 2015/The Week in Chess 1103 (132)}) 11. O-O Be7 12. Bd2 ({
White could have also thought about opening the position a bit for his pieces
with} 12. e4 $5 {This could also put black rook in danger after Be3.}) 12...
Nb6 13. c5 Nc4 14. Be1 b6 15. cxb6 Qxb6 16. Na4 $1 Qb5 (16... Qxb3 17. axb3 Nd6
18. Rc1 $16) 17. Rc1 O-O 18. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Gc5,Rc6][%cal Gb2b3] White was
definitely the one pressing in 1/2 (31) Nielsen,P (2687)-Nyback,T (2615)
Heidelberg GER 2010 (31), although black's defensive resources should never be
underestimated in the Slav.}) (7... Be6 {[%cal Gd5c4,Gb7b5,Gc6c5] is the
second most popular move, planning the exchange on c4, followed by b7-b5,
freeing the rook on a7. Therefore, the principled response is} 8. c5 {[%csl
Gc5,Re6,Re7] when Be6 is slightly misplaced, preventing black from playing
e7-e5, which is the most dangerous response to white closing down the center
with c4-c5.} g6 (8... g5 $6 {is taking Morozevich's favorite move a bit too
far. White obtained a clear advantage in} 9. Nf3 h6 10. Bd3 Bg7 11. Qc2 Nbd7
12. Bd2 Bg4 13. h4 $16 {[%csl Rg5] 1-0 Korotylev,A (2565)-Frolov,D (2401)/
Sochi 2004/CBM 101/[Huebner,R] (29)}) 9. Qc2 Bg7 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O $14 {
[%cal Gf2f4] White has a clear advantage in this line. As the following
variations show, he can succesfully deal with black's breaks e7-e5 and b7-b6.
Even the knight on h4 is not placed so badly as it enables f2-f4.} Ng4 (11...
Nbd7 12. f4 $1 $36 {[%csl Re6]}) (11... Bc8 12. f4 b6 13. cxb6 Qxb6 14. Nf3 a5
15. Na4 $36 {[%csl Gc5,Rc6][%cal Gf3e5,Gb2b3]}) 12. h3 Nh6 13. Bd2 Bc8 14. Nf3
Bf5 15. e4 $1 dxe4 16. Nxe4 $16 {[%csl Ra7,Rh6] 1-0 (52) Volkov,S (2623)
-Yilmaz,M (2530) Plovdiv BUL 2012}) ({Black had a few other tries - none of
them particularly successful.} 7... Be4 8. f3 dxc4 9. Qxc4 Bd5 10. Qe2 b5 11.
Qf2 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge3e4]} e6 12. e4 Bb4 13. a3 Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 Bb3 15. Rb1
Ba4 16. Be2 O-O 17. O-O $16 {1-0 Khismatullin,D (2681)-Popov,V (2546)/St
Petersburg 2014/EXT 2015 (33)}) (7... Bg4 8. h3 Bh5 {This risky move was
played in 1-0 Kuznetsov,E (2180)-Nebolsina,V (2320)/Tomsk 2011/EXT 2013 (36).
White could obtain a clear advantage by pressing against the d5 pawn:} 9. g4
Bg6 (9... g5 10. Ng2 Bg6 11. h4 $16) (9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 b5 11. Be2 Bg6 12. a4
$16) 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. g5 $1 {[%csl Rd5]} Ne4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. h4 $16 {[%csl
Re4]}) (7... e6 8. Nxf5 exf5 9. cxd5 cxd5 {1-0 Kersten,U (2339)-Czaeczine,A 
(2111)/Dresden 2003/EXT 2004 (40)} 10. Bd3 g6 {Here white can use a well-known
method against doubled f-pawns:} 11. h3 $1 Nc6 12. g4 $36 {[%csl Rd5]}) {Black
is getting ready to play in QGA fashion - dxc4, e6, b5 and c5. White can
hardly counter this plan directly, but he can make sure his pieces are in the
best possible positions to meet it. Thus} 8. Qc2 ({Ding Liren played
differently:} 8. Bd2 {and now Guseinov unleashed} b5 $1 9. Nf3 $5 dxc4 10. Bxc4
e6 (10... bxc4 $6 11. Qxb8 Rb7 12. Qa8 {[%csl Ra6,Rc4,Rc6] leaves black
queenside pawns too weak.}) 11. O-O c5 12. Rfd1 {Somewhat abstract.} ({White
can not count on any advantage even after a more natural} 12. Be2 Nbd7 13. Qc2
Bb7 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. b4 Be7 16. a4 bxa4 17. Rxa4 O-O $11 {[%csl Ra6,Rb4] and
black achieved all he wanted. Pawn on a6 isn't any weaker than the one on b4.})
12... Nbd7 13. Bf1 Bb7 14. Be1 {Here Guseinov made a strange positional mistake
} c4 $6 ({Instead} 14... Qb8 $1 $132 {[%cal Gf8d6] followed by Bd6 would have
given him excellent chances in the middlegame.}) 15. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Rb5,Rc4]
[%cal Ga2a4,Ge3e4]} Qc7 16. a4 b4 17. Nb1 Bd5 18. Rc1 $16 {[%csl Rc4] 1-0 Ding,
L (2782)-Guseinov,G (2634)/Baku 2015/EXT 2016 (41)}) 8... e6 9. Nf3 (9. b3 {
addresses dxc4, but Black gets a reasonable position after} c5 10. Nf3 cxd4 11.
exd4 b6 $11 {[%cal Ga7c7]}) 9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 c5 (10... b5 {is a little
premature due to} 11. Bd3 Nbd7 {[%csl Gc2,Gd3][%cal Gc6c5,Gc8b7] The position
resembles those that we analyzed in Repertoire against the Semi-Slav.} 12. Ne4
$1 {[%cal Gc2c6]} Nxe4 13. Bxe4 c5 14. Bd2 $1 $14 {[%cal Gd2a5] stopping Rc7.
Black has some development issues. For example} Bb7 15. Bxb7 Rxb7 16. O-O Be7
17. dxc5 Bxc5 18. Qe4 $36 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1,Gd2c3]}) 11. a4 Nc6 12.
O-O cxd4 (12... b6 13. Rd1 Rd7 14. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Ra6]}) {All this was played
in game Nyback-Koykka. Nyback went for the classical IQP position and didn't
get advantage. At this point, I suggest a different approach:} 13. Rd1 $1 $146
{[%cal Gf3d4,Gd1d8] More ambitious than exd4. Opening the position makes sense
with black rook misplaced on a7. The following lines generally prove that
white has, at the very least, an unpleasant initiative due to his development
advantage.} (13. exd4 Be7 14. Bg5 O-O 15. Rad1 b6 16. Qe2 Nb4 17. Ne5 Rc7 18.
Rfe1 Bb7 ({Black would also equalize with} 18... Nfd5 $11) 19. Nxf7 $5 Rxf7 20.
Bxe6 Nbd5 21. Nxd5 Nxd5 22. Bxf7+ Kxf7 23. Qh5+ Kg8 24. Re5 g6 25. Bxe7 Rxe7
$13 {White somehow muscled a win in this game, although the position is
objectively not better for white.  1-0 Nyback,T (2594)-Koykka,P (2307)/
Sastamala 2014/CBM 161 Extra (65)}) 13... b6 {Trying to connect the rook with
the rest of the forces.} (13... Be7 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. exd4 O-O 16. d5 $1 {
[%cal Gd1d8]} Qc7 17. Qe2 $36 {[%csl Ra7] is a clear example of what happens
when black fails to do so in time.}) 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 (14... Nb4 15. Qb3 Rd7 16.
Bd2 $36 {[%csl Ra6,Rb4,Rb6]}) 15. Rxd4 $1 (15. exd4 {also comes into
consideration} Bd6 16. d5 Qc7 17. Qe2 {with some complications.}) 15... Qc7 (
15... Rd7 16. Qe2 $36 {[%csl Ra6]}) (15... Bd7 16. Ne4 $1 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Bc5 18.
Rd3 O-O 19. Bd2 $36 {[%csl Ra7,Rd7]}) 16. Be2 $1 {Enabling Rc4.} (16. b3 Bd6
17. Ba3 Bxa3 18. Rxa3 O-O 19. Ra1 Bb7 20. Rad1 Raa8 21. Qe2 $14 {gives white
the slightest of positional plusses.}) 16... Bd7 (16... Bd6 17. Rc4 $36 {[%csl
Rc8]}) 17. e4 {[%cal Gc1g5]} Bd6 18. g3 O-O 19. Be3 $14 {White has a nice
advantage here thanks to better placed pieces. For example:} e5 20. Rxd6 $1
Qxd6 21. a5 $36 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Ga5b6]} *

