1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. e3 g6 {This is the most serious
sideline, employed very often by Gata Kamsky. Black shifts the game into
Schlechter variation territory, trying to justify a6 as a useful move in that
system.} ({Another sideline is} 5... Bg4 {when we play in the same fashion as
in Chapters 1 and 2:} 6. Qb3 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gb3b7]} Ra7 (6... b5 7. cxd5 Bxf3
{The only reasonable move.} (7... cxd5 $6 {gives white the essential tempo:} 8.
Ne5 Bf5 9. a4 {and we reach a position similar to CHAPTER 1, only with white
knight on e5, which makes a crucial difference. Black can not sacrifice the
pawn on b4, so he is forced to play} bxa4 10. Rxa4 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Rb7][%cal
Gb3b7] which is just bad for him.} e6 11. Qb7 Nbd7 12. Bb5 Qc8 13. Qxc8+ Rxc8
14. Rxa6 $18 {1-0 Jaeger,D (2057)-Igonin,P (2145)/Germany 2007/EXT 2009 (48)})
8. gxf3 cxd5 9. a4 b4 {Similarly to Chapter 1, black gets better chances if he
sacrifices this pawn to complete development.} (9... bxa4 10. Qxa4+ Nbd7 11. e4
e6 {1/2-1/2 Nikolakaros,K (1627)-Norri,R (1878)/Naantali 2012/CBM 149 Extra 
(27)} 12. Bb5 $1 $16 {[%csl Re8][%cal Ge4e5,Gc1g5] looks very suspicious for
black.}) 10. Qxb4 Nc6 11. Qb3 e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 {happened in Wells,P-Zschaebitz,
K/Dresden op/1996/1-0 (62) and here the best for white was} 13. Be2 $146 Qd7
14. f4 Nc6 15. O-O Bc5 16. Bf3 $16) (6... Bc8 {admits defeat from opening
standpoint. White's advantage is undesputable, but let us see how to proceed
from here:} 7. Bd3 e6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. a4 $1 Be7 10. a5 {[%csl Ga5,Rb7,Rc8] I
like this pawn march as it restricts black's queenside development.} O-O 11.
Rd1 Re8 12. Bd2 Bd6 13. e4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4] White finally opens up the
position.} dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 $16 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Rc6c5,Re6e5] 1-0
Sakaev,K (2555)-Levitt,J (2445)/Cappelle-la-Grande 1994/EXT 1999 (30)}) 7. Ne5
{[%csl Ge5,Rg4] Compared to 5...Bf5, this is a plus for white, which makes the
whole 5...Bg4 variation look dubious for black.} Be6 {[%cal Ge6d5] Black gives
support to a potentially vulnerable d5 pawn and hopes to complete development
with g7-g6, Bg7 etc.} (7... e6 $2 {[%csl Rg4] was terribly unkind to black
bishop, which soon found itself almost trapped.} 8. f3 Bf5 9. g4 Bg6 10. h4 {
[%csl Rg6]} h5 {This is a sad neccesity.} 11. Nxg6 fxg6 12. g5 Ng8 13. Bh3 $18
{[%csl Re6,Rg6][%cal Ge3e4] and black is positionally doomed with such a
horrid pawn structure.} Kf7 14. e4 Ne7 15. Bf4 b5 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. exd5 exd5
18. Bxb8 Qxb8 19. Nxd5 $18 {1-0 Krasenkow,M (2655)-Oll,L (2650)/Polanica Zdroj
1998/CBM 067/[Huebner,R] (28)}) (7... Bf5 {looks reasonable, but does not
solve black's problems as white has a strong retort} 8. f3 $1 {[%csl Rf5][%cal
Gg2g4,Gg4g5] Threatening to win the d5-pawn with g4-g5.} g6 (8... h6 9. cxd5
cxd5 10. e4 $1 {Now the blow comes in the center.} Be6 11. Be3 dxe4 12. d5 $18)
9. cxd5 cxd5 {and here white obtained a strong initiative with} 10. e4 $1 Be6
11. Bg5 Bg7 12. exd5 $1 Nxd5 13. Bc4 $16 Bxe5 14. Bxd5 Bxd5 15. Nxd5 Bd6 {in
Novik,M-Berezjuk,S/Bratislava op/1992/1-0 (57) and now simply} 16. Bh6 {[%csl
Ra7,Rb8,Rd6,Re8] would leave black completely busted.} Qa5+ 17. Kf2 Nc6 18.
Rhe1 $40 {[%csl Re8]}) 8. cxd5 cxd5 {The most principled.} ({Taking on d5 with
a piece promises an easy advantage to white.} 8... Bxd5 9. Qc2 g6 10. e4 Be6
11. Be3 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Gd4d5]} Ra8 12. h3 Bg7 13. Be2 O-O 14. O-O Ne8 15.
Rfd1 $16 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] 1-0 Bromberger,S (2407)-Langheinrich,F (2405)/
Augsburg 2002/CBM 087 Extra (55)}) (8... Nxd5 $6 9. e4 $1 Nxc3 (9... Nf6 10.
Qc2 Nbd7 11. Be3 Ra8 12. h3 $16) 10. Qxc3 Nd7 (10... g6 $6 11. d5 $1 cxd5 12.
Nxf7 $18 {[%csl Rh8]}) 11. Be3 Ra8 12. Bd3 Nxe5 13. dxe5 g6 14. O-O Bg7 15. f4
$16 {[%csl Rg7] 1-0 Sundararajan,K (2446)-Sumets,A (2534)/Barcelona 2008/CBM
126 Extra (43)}) 9. Bd2 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Ga1c1,Gc1c8] White is not in a hurry
to complete kingside development as he has better things to attend to on the
queenside.} g6 10. Rc1 Bg7 ({If black tries to swap the strong Ne5 with} 10...
Nc6 {he has to accept a hard life with a backward pawn on c6 after} 11. Nxc6
bxc6 12. Na4 $16 {[%csl Gc5,Rc6]} Bd7 13. Nc5 e6 14. Nxd7 Kxd7 15. Qa4 Qa8 16.
