11... Nxd7 12. Nxd5 $18) 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 $18 {1-0 Atalik,S (2616)-Fast,
N (2131)/Stillwater 2011/CBM 142 Extra/[Atalik,S] (26)}) 11. Qa4+ $1 {[%csl
Ra7][%cal Ga4a7] An important check for tactical reasons before black castles.}
Bd7 12. Nxd7 ({A good alternative was also} 12. Bb5 $5 Ra8 13. Nxd7 Nbxd7 14.
Bxd7+ Qxd7 15. Qxd7+ Kxd7 16. Na4 {[%csl Ga4,Rb6,Rc5,Gd2,Rf6,Rg7][%cal Gd2a5,
Yc1c8] Where white has the squares, the file, and better pieces.} Rab8 17. Nc5+
$16) 12... Qxd7 13. Qxd7+ {Here black blundered severely with} Nbxd7 $4 ({It
was necessary to play} 13... Kxd7 {with an obviously worse, but still playable
endgame.} 14. Bd3 $16 {[%csl Ra7,Gd2,Gd3,Rd7,Rg7][%cal Gc3a4]}) 14. Nb5 $1 {
[%csl Ra7][%cal Gc1c8] 1-0 Kuljasevic,D (2419)-Dabo Peranic,R (2341)/Rabac
2003/CBM 096 ext}) 6. Bd3 {I think white should use the opportunity to play
this move since black has wasted a move on a6. In the main line of Schlechter
variation Be2 is considered a bit more precise than Bd3, but here white should
not fear Bg4 as he always has Qb3.} Bg7 7. O-O O-O (7... b5 {[%cal Gb5c4] is
an interesting idea to achieve a hybrid between Chebanenco and Schlechter. I
used it once as a surprise weapon against a theoretically well-prepared
Russian GM Lysij and it worked like a charm. However, objectively speaking
white should be better with accurate play:} 8. b3 {Similarly to our play in
the main line Chebanenco, I believe this flexible move is the best.} O-O 9. Bb2
Nbd7 ({Sometimes black try to solve the issue of light-squared bishop in the
following manner:} 9... Bf5 {[%cal Gf5d3]} 10. Bxf5 gxf5 {[%csl Rf5] but at
the cost of spoiling his pawn structure.} 11. Ne5 Nfd7 12. f4 {[%csl Ge5]} f6
13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. Rc1 $14 {[%csl Rb8,Rg7] 1-0 Mareco,S (2568)-Gimenez,S (2238)/
