2-1/2 Doroshkievich,V-Lobzhanidze,D/Cherkessk 1997/EXT 99 (43)} {I believe
white should prepare his forces for the fight along the c-file.} 11. Rfc1 Qa5 {
[%cal Gb5c4]} (11... e6 12. cxb5 cxb5 13. Rc2 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rc7,Rg7][%cal
Gc1c8] Bg7 is not placed well in this kind of position.}) {Black is trying to
play on the queenside, but white can show him that this is his domain with a
resolute:} 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. b4 $1 Qxb4 14. a4 $16 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gb2a3,
Ga3e7]}) {Several moves were tried in this position. The most straightforward
is} 11. e4 ({while the most common one is} 11. Rfd1) ({An interesting idea is} 
11. cxd5 $5 cxd5 12. b4 $14 {[%cal Ga2a4]}) 11... Nh5 ({Winning the bishop
pair with} 11... b4 12. Na4 dxe4 13. Bxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 {[%csl Rb7,Gc5] does
not mean much when one of your bishops is buried on b7.} Re8 15. Ne5 $1 Nxe5
16. dxe5 Qc7 17. Qe3 $16 {[%csl Rb7,Rg7][%cal Ga4c5] 1-0 Malaniuk,V (2505)
-Panbukchian,V (2325)/Pula 1990/EXT 2000 (35)}) 12. g3 dxc4 (12... e5 $5 {was
a more testing move, creating chaos in the center:} 13. cxb5 axb5 14. dxe5 Nxe5
15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. exd5 Re8 17. Rfe1 $1 Nf6 18. Ne4 $14) 13. bxc4 Nb6 $6 {This
is weak.} (13... e5 {was essential, when} 14. d5 $14 {[%csl Gd5,Rh5] keeps
