Bxe7 Rfe8 19. Bg5 $16 {1-0 Malakhov,V (2670)-Sergienko,S (2456)/Sochi 2005/CBM
107 (29)}) {And we reached the position from Schlechter variation with the
move a6 instead of Bg4. Gata Kamsky defended black side in many games with
very good results. It suits his style perfectly - the positions are somewhat
passive, but complex and with very little theory. If white underestimates
black's setup and plays without a particular plan, black can surely get a good
position. We should, therefore, make sure to study this variation properly,
regardless of a relative lack of theoretical material. Among several
alternatives, such as 8.h3, 8.b3 and 8.a4, I recommend:} 8. Qb3 {[%csl Rb7,Rc8]
[%cal Gb3b7,Gb3d5] which is consistent with our general approach to Chebanenco
- putting pressure on b7 when possible. This hampers black's ideal development
related to Bg4, so he needs to make a concession.} dxc4 {[%cal Gb7b5] The most
logical continuation as black relieves the pressure off the d5 and b7 pawns.} (
{The main alternative is} 8... e6 {in Semi-Slav style, only with black bishop
on g7 rather than d6. White's response is natural:} 9. e4 {[%cal Gc1g5]} dxe4
10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Qc7 {This seems to be the best move. Before developing
the knight, black prevents Bf4.} ({Kamsky once made that mistake:} 11... Nd7 $6
{and after} 12. Bf4 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gf4d6] his development became problematic.
} c5 $6 {Continuing on the wrong path} ({The pawn sacrifice to complete
development was called for:} 12... e5 $5 13. dxe5 Nc5 {[%cal Gc8g4]} 14. Qc2
Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Bf5 16. Qe3 Qd3 17. Qc1 $14 {[%csl Ge5] though black does not
have quite enough compensation.}) 13. Rad1 cxd4 14. Bd6 Re8 15. c5 $1 $16 {
[%csl Gd6][%cal Gc5c6] Very strong play by Wang Hao. He sacrifices a pawn to
obtain strong initiative.} Qa5 16. c6 bxc6 17. Nxd4 $1 Nc5 18. Nxc6 Nxb3 19.
Nxa5 Nxa5 20. Bxa8 $18 {1-0 Wang Hao-Kamsky,G SportAccord Blitz Men Beijing
2012 (40)}) ({The first time Kamsky played this variation, he went for a
positionally risky operation} 11... f5 12. Bc2 c5 ({Of course, giving up the
strong bishop} 12... Bxd4 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Bh6 Re8 15. Rad1 $40 {[%csl Ra8,
Rb8,Rc8,Rf6,Rg7,Rg8] is not worth a pawn.}) 13. dxc5 Nc6 {[%cal Ge6e5,Ge5e4]
He was hoping to compensate for the pawn by having a strong kingside majority.
Here white can improve the game with active} 14. Rd1 $146 ({over tepid} 14. Be3
e5 15. Rad1 Qe7 16. Rd6 e4 17. Nd4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Bxd4 19. Rxd4 Qxc5 $11 {and
black equalized in 1/2-1/2 Onischuk,A (2666)-Kamsky,G (2741)/Saint Louis 2013/
CBM 154 Extra (30)}) 14... Qe7 15. Rd6 e5 16. Bd2 e4 17. Re1 $1 $14 {[%csl Gd6]
when black's compensation is doubtful.}) 12. c5 $1 {[%csl Gc5] We have seen
how annoying this move is for black in the Semi-Slav. Black can now only hope
to gain some space with e6-e5:} Nd7 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 13. Bg5 {[%csl Rd6][%cal
Gg5e7,Ge7d6]} Re8 {and here we can improve on Mamedyarov's game against Kamsky
with} 14. Rac1 $146 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc1c5] This move gives support to the
c-pawn, so that e6-e5 can be answered with d4-d5.} ({Black eventually
equalized after} 14. Rfe1 e5 15. Bd3 Nf8 $1 {[%cal Gc8g4]} 16. Nxe5 Be6 17. Bc4
Bxc4 18. Qxc4 Bxe5 19. dxe5 Rxe5 {etc. in 1/2-1/2 Mamedyarov,S (2761)-Kamsky,G
(2763)/Beijing 2013/CBM 156 (36)}) 14... Nf6 (14... e5 $6 {is not recommended}
15. d5 cxd5 16. Bxd5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd5][%cal Rd5f7]} Nf6 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Nd2 $16
{[%cal Gd2e4,Ge4d6]}) 15. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Gb6,Rc8,Gd3,Gd6,Gg5] and white enjoys
a slight advantage due to more space for his pieces.}) ({A rare, but sensible
possibility is} 8... Ra7 {[%cal Ga7b7,Gc8f5] I was not too happy with how
white handled this position in practice, so I recommend a new move} 9. Bd2 $5
$146 {simply finishing development and allowing black to accomplish his idea -}
Bf5 {However, after} 10. Bxf5 gxf5 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5]} e6 13.
Rac1 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Rg7][%cal Gc1c8,Gc3a4] it is obvious that white will have
a durable initiative on the queenside.}) 9. Bxc4 b5 {Again, the most logical
continuation. Black relieves the pressure off the b7 with a tempo.} ({Kamsky
once played an interesting idea} 9... Ne8 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Ge8d6,Gd6b7,Gg7a1]
though of course, such time consuming maneuvres can hardly be critical.} 10.
Rd1 Nd6 11. Be2 Bg4 12. e4 Nd7 13. e5 ({White can also achieve a stable
advantage with} 13. h3 $5 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 $14 {and if black trades queens} Qb6
15. Qxb6 Nxb6 16. Bg5 Rfe8 {white has better chances in the endgame as well.}
17. Rac1 $14 {[%csl Rb6,Gd4,Ge4,Gf3,Gg5]}) 13... Nb5 14. a4 Nxc3 15. bxc3 b5 {
This was all played in 0-1 Karjakin,S (2786)-Kamsky,G (2741)/Zug 2013/CBM 154/
[Sumets,A] Here Karjakin spoiled the advantage by playing a4-a5. Instead he
could have gotten better chances with} 16. c4 $146 Be6 17. Be3 Rb8 18. Ng5 bxc4
19. Qc3 Bd5 20. Bxc4 e6 21. a5 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Rc6,Rg7] Black is solid, but
cramped.}) 10. Be2 {[%csl Gd4,Ge3][%cal Gf1d1] This position closely resembles
the Russian system of the Gruenfeld defense with a6. The difference is that
white has castled here and did not play e4 yet. It should probably work
slightly in white's favor as his position in the center is more stable this
way and this means something in the Gruenfeld.} Bf5 {This is the most common
move and the one that Kamsky has played most regularly. Its purpose is to
prevent e3-e4.} ({Playing according to the afore-mentioned line of the
Gruenfeld with:} 10... c5 {is not as principled here since white is more
stable in the center, as we already said. He can take the pawn} 11. dxc5 {and
black is hard-pressed to find the most suitable way to return it, which is
usually not the case in the corresponding Gruenfeld line. For example:} Nbd7 (
11... Qc7 12. a4 $1 {[%csl Rb5]} Nbd7 (12... bxa4 13. Nxa4 {[%csl Gc5][%cal
Ga4c5]}) 13. axb5 Nxc5 14. Qb4 Rb8 15. Bd2 axb5 {Karpov,A-Ljubojevic,L
Amsterdam 1988 1/2-1/2 (79) and here white should have inserted} 16. Rfc1 $1 {
[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc1c7] forcing} Ne6 {and only then take the pawn} 17. Nxb5 $16
{[%csl Gb2]}) 12. c6 (12. Qa3 $6 Rb8 13. b4 Nxc5 $1 $11 {allowed black to
equalize easily in 1/2-1/2 Kruppa Y - Itkis,B Platonov Memorial 3-rd Kiev 2005}
) 12... Nb8 13. a4 $1 {[%csl Rb5] This is the key move in such positions, as
we have also seen in Karpov's game above.} Be6 14. Qa3 Nxc6 15. axb5 axb5 16.
Qxa8 Qxa8 17. Rxa8 Rxa8 18. Bxb5 $14 {with an extra pawn in the endgame,
though black has fighting chances.}) ({Similarly, in response to black's
double fianchetto} 10... Bb7 {white should play} 11. a4 {[%csl Gb3,Rb5,Rb7]
[%cal Gb3b7] The queen is placed perfectly on b3 in this line.} Nbd7 12. e4 c5
{Black needs to open up the position now, even at a price of one pawn;
otherwise he would get shut-down.} 13. e5 Ng4 14. dxc5 Ngxe5 ({If} 14... Nxc5
15. Qb4 Qc8 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rxa8 Bxa8 18. e6 $1 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rg4][%cal
Gb4g4,Gb4c5] is a very nice tactical way to obtain advantage.}) 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 {
and here in the game 1/2-1/2 Wotulo,M (2330)-Lombard,A (2380)/Siegen 1970/EXT
2002 white should have simply defended the c-pawn with} 16. Be3 $146 {[%csl
Gc5][%cal Ge2b5,Ge3c5] which would lead to a typical Gruenfeld position. White
has a nice advantage, for example:} Qc7 17. axb5 Nxc5 18. Bxc5 Qxc5 19. bxa6
$16 {[%csl Ga6]}) ({Black can also try to develop the queenside more subtly -} 
10... Nbd7 {and now} 11. e4 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Ge4e5] is appropriate} (11. a4 {
is not so strong without the bishop on b7 and black can play} Rb8 12. axb5 {
0-1 Gritsak,O (2550)-Miroshnichenko,E (2483)/Polanica Zdroj 1999 (39)} cxb5 $1
$13 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gd7b6]}) 11... Nb6 ({Black is not ready for} 11... c5 $6 12.
e5 $16 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Ge5f6,Ge5e6]}) ({The other pawn break is interesting,
though:} 11... e5 $5 $146 12. dxe5 Ng4 13. e6 Nc5 14. exf7+ Rxf7 {with a
typical initiative for sacrificed pawn. However, white has a strong defense in}
15. Qd1 $1 {and if black tries to go for checkmate with} Qc7 {white keeps his
extra pawn with} 16. h3 Rxf3 17. hxg4 $1 Rf7 18. Be3 $14) {In this position,
white has more than one way to keep a stable advantage:} 12. Bf4 {was choice
of young Carlsen.} (12. Rd1 {is good, too.} Be6 13. Qc2 Qc7 14. a4 $1 Rfc8 ({If
} 14... b4 {white has} 15. a5 $1 Nbd7 16. Na4 Qxa5 17. Ng5 Qc7 18. Nxe6 fxe6
19. Bc4 $16 {[%csl Rc6,Re6,Re7]}) 15. a5 Nbd7 $6 {[%csl Rd7]} (15... Nc4 $142
$14) 16. h3 Ne8 17. Be3 $16 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Re6,Re8] Edouard,R-Villegas,P 12 th
Ch-EUR Aix-les-Bains FRA 2011 1-0 (39)}) 12... Be6 13. Qc2 Bc4 14. Rfd1 Rc8 15.
Rac1 Bxe2 16. Qxe2 {Black has alleviated his position a little bit with the
trade of light-squared bishops, but he is still suffering.} Qd7 17. h3 Qb7 18.
Bg5 Rfe8 19. e5 Nfd5 20. Ne4 $14 {[%csl Gc5,Rc6,Rg7] Carlsen,M-Malakhov,V FIDE
World-Cup Khanty Mansiysk 2005 1-0 (34)}) ({Finally, a very interesting option
is} 10... a5 $5 {where black remains flexible with his options and prevents
