the most logical one. The queen can become exposed on b3 after a5-a4, while
from c2 it supports the key square e4.} b4 (11... Nbd7 $6 {is too passive and
white is just better after} 12. e4 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4]} Nb6 13. Rd1 b4 14. Nb1
Bb7 15. Be3 Rc8 16. Nbd2 Ng4 17. Bf4 Nd7 18. Nb3 $16 {1-0 Burmakin,V (2599)
-Wachinger,G (2248)/Bad Wiessee 2009/EXT 2010 (34)}) 12. Ne4 $1 Nxe4 13. Qxe4
Ba6 (13... Bf5 14. Qh4 $14) 14. Bxa6 Rxa6 {This position first appeared in 1/
2-1/2 Bacrot,E (2725)-Kamsky,G (2741)/Thessaloniki 2013/CBM 155 (49). Bacrot
did not react so well and he had to fight for a draw. The improvement was
found a bit later:} 15. a3 $1 c5 $1 {[%cal Gg7b2,Ga6f6] Critical.} (15... Qd6 {
is too passive and gave white an easy advantage in the following game:} 16. Bd2
Rb6 17. axb4 axb4 18. Rfc1 Nd7 {1/2-1/2 Han,C (2079)-Liou,Y (2417)/Saint Louis
2015/CBM 167 Extra} {The most covincing is} 19. Ra5 $14 {[%csl Ga5,Rb4,Rb6,Gc1,
Rc6]}) 16. dxc5 Qc7 {Black will regain that pawn as white is not developed
enough to defend it.} 17. Nd4 Qxc5 18. Bd2 $14 {However, the resulting
position is still slightly in white's favor as black will surely end up with a
