1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. e3 b5 6. b3 Bf5 {This is a less
popular, but quite playable alternative to Bg4.} 7. Ne5 {[%cal Gg2g4] I have
always thought that this move is more principled} ({than the more common} 7.
Bd3 {When I set out to investigate the reasons for greater popularity of this
move over 6.Ne5, I thought I would find a definite proof of white's advantage.
However, to my surprise, achieving advantage with Bd3 is far from simple in
both} e6 ({and} 7... Bxd3 8. Qxd3 e6) 8. Bxf5 exf5 {I could be missing
something, but I was not too impressed with white's outlook if black plays
accurately.}) 7... h6 {[%cal Gf5h7] This should be the right move for black,
so that he can park his bishop on h7 in case of g2-g4.} ({Other moves are
risky in that respect. The most common one is} 7... e6 {and then, of course,
we continue:} 8. g4 Bg6 (8... Ne4 $2 {was a really bad idea} 9. gxf5 Nxc3 10.
Qh5 Qf6 11. fxe6 $18 {in 1-0 Kuljasevic,D (2408)-Jirka,J (2408)/Zemplinska
Sirava 2004/CBM 100 Extra (19)}) 9. h4 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh4h5] Black's
light-squared bishop is in trouble and we know from CHAPTER 3 that pushing
h-pawn leads to irreparable damage to black's pawn structure. He should,
therefore, look for other ways to counter white's threat.} {The most popular
move is} Bb4 (9... Ne4 {used to be considered fine for black some time ago,
until Aronian found the right way for white.} 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. f3 f6 {[%csl
Re4,Re5] In many lines of this variation, Black counts on this counter-attack
to get his bishop out of the hot water. However, in this particular instance
white has a counter-attack of his own:} 12. Nxc6 $1 Nxc6 13. fxe4 dxe4 {[%csl
Gc1,Re1,Re4,Gf1] The arising position is imbalanced. White's bishop pair and
superior pawn structure should account for advantage, but his king is a bit
unsafe, which is always a concern when one pushes his kingside pawns too far
in the opening. Having all this in mind, Aronian's continuation} 14. Bd2 $14 {
[%cal Rf8b4]} Qb8 15. Rh3 $1 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Rb8g3] is to the point as he
denies black any attempts to endanger the king. Black did not find the right
way out of this complex position and soon was lost:} f5 16. cxb5 axb5 17. gxf5
exf5 18. a4 $1 bxa4 19. bxa4 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gf1b5]} Kd8 20. Bb5 $18 {1-0
Aronian,L (2649)-Kindermann,S (2542)/Germany 2004/CBM 101 (30)}) (9... Nbd7 {
was a recent try by Slav specialist GM Dragan Solak,} 10. Nxd7 Kxd7 (10... Nxd7
$2 11. h5 Be4 12. f3 $18) {but I do not see how black can avoid getting into a
worse position after} 11. h5 $146 ({Instead of} 11. c5 h5 12. g5 Ne4 13. Nxe4
Bxe4 14. f3 Bg6 15. a4 $14 {[%cal Ga1a8] which was also better for white in
1-0 Navara,D (2705)-Solak,D (2618)/Warsaw POL 2013/The Week in Chess 992 (58),
although by a smaller margin.}) 11... Bb4 12. Bd2 Qa5 13. Rc1 Ne4 14. hxg6 Nxc3
15. Qc2 Ne4 16. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 17. Kd1 $16 {because he can not take on} hxg6 (17...
bxc4 18. gxh7 {[%csl Gh7]}) (17... fxg6 18. f3 Ng3 19. cxd5 $1 {[%csl Rd7]}) {
due to} 18. Rxh8 Rxh8 19. cxd5 $1 $18 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gc1c7] and in this
instance the weakening of black's structure with b7-b5 is decisive.}) 10. Bd2
Bxc3 (10... Qa5 {is too risky} 11. Rc1 Ne4 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. f3 f6 (13... dxc4
{[%cal Gc4c3] was a creative try to complicate matters in 0-1 Van den
Bersselaar,J (2175)-Saltaev,M (2484)/Hertogenbosch 2003/CBM 095 Extra (26).
However, white can simply continue} 14. Bxb4 $146 Qxb4+ 15. Kf2 {[%csl Re4]} f6
16. Nxc4 $1 bxc4 17. Rxc4 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gc4b4] This is why it was important
to take on b4 first. This move comes with a crucial tempo.} Qb7 18. fxe4 $18 {
and white ends up with extra pawn and a dominant position.}) 14. fxe4 fxe5 {An
interesting situation in the center. Fortunately, white can come out on top
from these complications with} 15. cxd5 exd5 16. exd5 exd4 {1-0 Meyer,M (2285)
-Karhanek,P (2142)/Stare Mesto 2007/CBM 119 Extra} 17. Bxb4 $1 $146 {Again
