1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. e3 b5 6. b3 Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gb8d7,
Gf8d6] This has been the main line of Chebanenco Slav for a long time. There
is nothing more natural than developing a piece with a pin. Black is hoping to
follow it up with e6, Nbd7, Bd6, 0-0 and gradually equalize the game.} 7. Be2 {
Among many attempts to get advantage, I am the most keen on this principled
move.} ({If white tries to pursue the bishop immediately with} 7. h3 {black
has a nice tactical retort:} Bxf3 8. Qxf3 e5 $1 9. dxe5 Bb4 {[%csl Rc3][%cal
Gb4e1] using the unprotected knight to develop counterplay. After the forced}
10. Bd2 Bxc3 11. Bxc3 Ne4 12. Bb4 bxc4 $13 {The game becomes double-edged, but
the final verdict about this line seems to be closer to a draw than anything
else.}) ({Other interesting possiblities are} 7. Bd2) (7. Qc2) ({and} 7. a4)
7... Nbd7 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd7e5] This is less popular than 7...e6. Black
wants to take e5 square under control before completing kingside development.
We remain unfazed and continue with our plan:} 8. h3 {[%csl Rg4]} Bh5 (8... Bf5
{makes no difference as after} 9. g4 {the bishop has to return to} Bg6 {anyway,
so we transpose into the main line after} 10. Ne5) ({The exchange on f3} 8...
Bxf3 {is also possible and covered in the next chapter} 9. Bxf3 e6 {- CHAPTER 6
} ({The only independent try would be} 9... e5 $6 {but it is not fully correct
as white proved in the following game:} 10. cxd5 Bb4 11. Bd2 exd4 12. Ne2 $1
Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 Nxd5 14. Nxd4 {[%csl Rc6] It became obvious that opening the
center with a weak pawn on c6 was not a good idea. White won a pawn after} Ne5
15. Nxc6 Nxf3+ 16. gxf3 $16 {1-0 Fridman,D (2627)-Van Kampen,R (2475)/
Hilversum 2008/CBM 123 Extra (57)})) 9. g4 Bg6 10. Ne5 {[%csl Rc6,Ge5,Rg6]
With Nbd7, the attack comes to c6 pawn as well. So black should trade off the
powerful knight:} Nxe5 ({The only notable alternative is} 10... bxc4 11. bxc4
e6 {when taking on c6 is not good, so white should go for the bishop pair:} 12.
Nxg6 (12. Nxc6 $6 Qc7 {[%csl Rc6] and white does not have cxb5 to defend the
knight - that was the purpose of the exchange on c4 on the previous move.})
12... hxg6 13. c5 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Rc6][%cal Gb1b8] However, the exchange on c4
favors white in this pawn structure as now he can more easily attack weak
black pawns on the queenside than with pawns on b3 and b5.} g5 14. f4 {[%csl
Ge5] Also taking important e5 square under control.} gxf4 15. exf4 g6 16. Be3
Bg7 17. Rb1 Rb8 18. Rxb8 Qxb8 {Black was passive, but relatively solid in 1-0 
