way to continue was} 19. Bf3 $14 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd1d2,Ge1f2]}) 11. dxe5 Nd7 (
{An important alternative is} 11... Ne4 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. f3 Bg6 14. cxd5 cxd5
15. a4 {[%csl Ra6,Rb5] It is important to soften up black's queenside.} b4 {
[%csl Ra6,Rb4] and here white has a strong resource:} 16. e6 $1 {[%csl Rf8]
[%cal Ga1h8] The purpose of this pawn sacrifice is to hinder black's
development and open up the diagonal a1-h8.} ({A calmer option is} 16. Bb2 e6
17. Rc1 Be7 18. Qd4 O-O 19. O-O {where white has a pleasant initiative along
the c-file, which bear fruit in the following game:} a5 ({though black may be
close to equality after} 19... Rc8 $1 20. Bxa6 $140 Rc2 $1 $132) 20. f4 Be4 21.
Bd3 Bxd3 22. Qxd3 Qd7 23. Rc2 Rfc8 24. Rfc1 $14 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gc2c8] 1-0
Topalov,V (2751)-Laznicka,V (2678)/Eilat ISR 2012/The Week in Chess 937 (44)  
(29)}) 16... Qd6 $1 {Black declines the Greek gift.} ({since after} 16... fxe6
$6 17. Bb2 $32 {[%csl Gb2,Re8,Rf8,Rh8] completing development may become
