18. Kd1 {[%csl Gd1]} fxe6 19. Qxb4 $14 {since in this double-edged position
white has a better piece coordination.}) {This has all been seen before and
here I propose an improvement for white:} 18. Bd2 $1 $146 {[%csl Rb4] Shifting
gears a little bit.} ({In the previous game, white focused purely on
positional compensation:} 18. Bb2 {[%cal Gb2g7]} Qd6 19. Rc1 e6 (19... f6 $5)
20. h4 f6 21. a5 Be7 22. h5 Bf7 23. h6 $44 {1-0 Rajlich,I (2421)-Murariu,A 
(2461)/Budapest 2006 (38)}) 18... Qd6 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 19. Bxb4 Qg3+ 20. Kd2 {
[%csl Gd2]} e6 (20... e5 {looks active, but is not appropriate with his king
still on e8.} 21. Qb6 Bxb4+ 22. Qxb4 $40 {[%csl Re8]}) 21. Bxf8 Kxf8 22. Rac1
$14 {[%csl Ga4,Ra6,Gb3,Gd4][%cal Gc1c8] and we reach an interesting new
position where i prefer white due to dominant position in the center and
better prospects on the queenside.}) 12. cxd5 e6 $5 {[%cal Gf8b4] An
unexpected answer. But we know from previous analysis that black does not mind
