pair of knights on the board, which might give white extra attacking
possiblities.} Qb6 {White's compensation for the pawn is obvious, though I
propose a small improvement at this point:} 15. Rc1 $146 {[%cal Gc1c8]} ({over
the stem game} 15. h4 {where black went wrong with} h5 $6 ({Instead} 15... Qb7
16. h5 Bf7 $13 {[%cal Ge6e5] was more to the point.}) 16. gxh5 Bf5 $2 (16...
Bf7) 17. Nxd5 $1 $18 {and soon lost in 1-0 Ding Liren (2766)-Movsesian,S (2653)
/Huai'an CHN 2016/The Week in Chess 1112 (34)}) 15... Bf7 16. O-O {White
completed development. Black can try to untangle in several different ways,
but in any case white obtains initiative:} Qb7 {[%cal Ge6e5]} (16... Rg8 {
[%cal Gg7g5,Gf8g7]} 17. a4 b4 18. a5 $1 Qxa5 19. Na4 g5 20. Qc2 $1 Bg6 21. Qc6
$18) (16... Qd6 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 17. Bxb5 $1 axb5 18. Nxb5 Qb8 19. Nc7+ Kd8 20.
Nxa8 Qxa8 21. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2c7]} Qb7 22. Qc3 $1 $40 {[%cal Gc3a5]}) 17. e4 $1
$36 {This would be a really fun position to play with white pieces.}) {White
tried several moves in this position. After some analysis, I came to
