1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. e3 b5 6. b3 Bg4 7. Be2 e6 8. h3 {In
this chapter, our main focus will be the position that arises after} Bxf3 ({If
black retreats to} 8... Bf5 {then we continue the same as usual} 9. g4 {[%csl
Rf5][%cal Gg4f5] when the game would transpose to the last two chapters after}
Bg6 ({unless black tries to be creative with} 9... Be4 10. g5 Nfd7 11. Nxe4
dxe4 12. Nd2 Bb4 13. Kf1 $1 Bxd2 14. Qxd2 Qxg5 15. Ba3 $1 $16 {[%csl Re8][%cal
Gh1g1]} bxc4 16. Rg1 Qf6 17. Rc1 $1 cxb3 18. Qb4 $18 {[%csl Ga3,Ra8,Gb4,Rb8,
Re8,Rh8][%cal Gb4b7] Black got completely demolished in 1-0 (34) Rajlich,I 
(2428)-Ovod,E (2410) Dresden 2007}) ({or} 9... Ne4 10. gxf5 Nxc3 11. Qc2 Ne4 (
11... Nxe2 12. Kxe2 $36) 12. fxe6 {1-0 (30) Akopian,V (2681)-Kindermann,S 
(2519) Porto Carras 2011} fxe6 13. Bd3 Bb4+ 14. Ke2 $16 {Either way, white
should be happy about his chances.})) 9. Bxf3 {[%csl Gc1,Gf3] With such a
pragmatic approach, black avoids all the fuss after Bh5, g4 etc. and gets a
playable position. The catch is that he has given up the bishop pair without
any fight, which gives white better long-term prospects. Still, as white we
need to know how to continue in order to capitalize on our recent acquiry.}
Nbd7 (9... Bb4 {would most likely just transpose to the main line after} 10.
Qc2 O-O 11. O-O Nbd7) 10. O-O {At this junction, black has three ways to
develop his bishop:} Bd6 {This seems the most natural to me as black's
counterplay in such positions should be related to e6-e5 break and he needs
the bishop on d6 to support it.} ({A more modest development is} 10... Be7 11.
Qc2 O-O {and here white can attack black's queenside with} 12. a4 $1 {[%csl
Rb5] Black can deal with it in the following ways:} Rc8 (12... Qc7 13. Ne2 $14
{[%cal Gc2c7]}) (12... bxc4 13. bxc4 a5 14. Bb2 Nb6 15. c5 Nbd7 $6 {Too
passive.} (15... Nc4 {was risky, but principled.} 16. Bc1 e5 $1 17. Be2 exd4
18. exd4 Rb8 19. Re1 $14) {Now white has an easy plan:} 16. Nb1 $1 {[%csl Ra5]
[%cal Gb2c3,Gb1d2,Gd2b3]} Qc7 17. Nd2 Ra7 18. Bc3 $16 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gb1b8]
1-0 Ganguly,S (2610)-Pham,L (2387)/Jakarta 2012/EXT 2013 (57)}) (12... b4 13.
Nb1 Rc8 14. Nd2 c5 15. Bb2 $14 {[%csl Gb2,Gf3] and white is looking forward to
the opening of the center with his bishops ready in their positions.}) 13. axb5
{[%cal Ga1a8] A logical reaction to black's previous move.} axb5 14. c5 $14 {
[%csl Gc5]} e5 15. Bd2 Ra8 16. Na2 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Rc6][%cal Ga2b4] A nice and
typical knight maneuvre.} Qc7 17. Nb4 exd4 18. exd4 $16 {with a clear
positional advantage for white in 1/2-1/2 Gulko,B (2615)-Short,N (2655)/New
York 1994/CBM 042/[Hertneck] (41)}) (10... Bb4 {is possible as well, though
maybe just to gain a tempo to complete development.} 11. Qc2 O-O 12. a3 Bxc3
13. Qxc3 $14 {There should be no doubt about white's advantage. He just needs
to open up the position.} bxc4 14. bxc4 Nb6 $6 {Strange play by Shirov in this
game.} (14... Ne4 $142) 15. c5 Nbd7 16. Rb1 Re8 17. Bd2 e5 18. Rb7 $16 {[%csl
Gb7,Rc6] 1-0 Vyzmanavin,A (2610)-Shirov,A (2705)/Moscow 1994/CBM 040 Extra (46)
}) 11. Bb2 O-O ({Opening up the b-file:} 11... bxc4 12. bxc4 {again favors
white more than black:} Rb8 13. Rb1 Qa5 14. c5 Bc7 15. Qd3 e5 16. Be2 O-O 17.
Ba1 Rxb1 18. Rxb1 exd4 19. exd4 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Rc6][%cal Gb1b7] 1-0 Almagro
Llamas,P (2442)-Bolado Saez,S (2388)/Madrid 2013/EXT 2014 (48)}) 12. Rc1 {I
prefer this patient useful move} ({over the direct} 12. e4 b4 13. e5 (13. Nxd5
$5 exd5 14. e5 Be7 ({but black should rather keep his bishop on the same
diagonal} 14... Bc7 15. exf6 Nxf6 16. a3 Re8 17. Qc2 bxa3 18. Bxa3 Ne4 $132 {
[%csl Gc7,Ge4]}) 15. exf6 Nxf6 16. a3 a5 17. Qc2 Re8 18. c5 $14 {1-0 Lou,Y 
(2443)-Lin,C (2520)/Zaozhuang 2015/EXT 2016 (42)}) 13... bxc3 14. Bxc3 Be7 15.
exf6 Bxf6 16. Rc1 Re8 17. Re1 $14 {where white has a symbolic advantage, but
it is not clear where he will break through. 1-0 Sethuraman,S (2527)-Dao,T 
(2512)/Mashhad 2011/CBM 142 (44)}) 12... Rc8 (12... Qe7 $6 {is inaccurate for
tactical reasons.} 13. Qc2 ({Actually,} 13. e4 {should have been played
immediately.}) 13... Rac8 14. e4 b4 15. e5 {[%cal Ge5d6,Gd6e7] The point is
that we can now take the bishop on d6, which was not possible in 12.e4 b4 13.
e5 bxc3 variation.} bxc3 16. exd6 Qxd6 17. Qxc3 {[%csl Gb2,Gf3] without the
dark-squared bishop, black can not play on the dark-squares, so white has a
clear advantage.} Qb8 18. Qa5 $16 {[%csl Ga5,Ra6,Rc6] 1-0 Dunn,A (2196)-Hunt,M
(2087)/Sunningdale 2007/EXT 2008 (42)}) 13. Qe2 {These positions require
patient maneuvering for a while, but the position will open up eventually.} Qe7
14. a4 $1 {As we have seen in 10...Be7 variation, this is the principled way
to pry into black's solid structure. The pressure on b5 becomes unbearable, so
black has to change the pawn structure in some way:} bxc4 ({Alternatively} 
14... b4 15. Nb1 a5 {leaves him with some weak squares on the queenside.} 16.
cxd5 $1 cxd5 17. Qb5 {[%csl Ra5,Gb5][%cal Gc1c8]} Ra8 18. Nd2 Rfb8 19. Qd3 Rc8
{and finally white is ready to open up the center} 20. e4 $14 {[%cal Gf3a8]
with a small, but stable advantage.}) 15. bxc4 a5 16. c5 $14 {[%csl Rc6] We
have seen a plenty of examples where white forces this pawn structure hoping
to exploit the weakness of c6 pawn in the future.} Bc7 17. e4 $1 {Excellent
play by the Chinese GM. By playing e4 himself, he prevents black from
obtaining counterplay with e6-e5.} ({as in} 17. Rb1 e5 $132) 17... dxe4 18.
Nxe4 Nd5 19. Nc3 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc3d5] Another strong move that shows
Yu's positional understanding.} Qg5 20. Nxd5 exd5 {White is much more
comfortable with black pawn on d5 rather than the knight. He can now proceed
to his main plan.} 21. Rb1 {[%cal Gb1b7]} Rfe8 22. Bc1 $1 {[%csl Rd4,Rg5][%cal
Gb1b7,Gc1e3] Absolutely clinical play by white in this game. He combines
strategy and tactics in the right way.} Qg6 23. Be3 $14 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gb1b7]
White has secured his weak pawn on d4 and is ready to invade the 7th rank with
his rook. Black can, of course, put up a stubborn defense, but this was
obviously not his intention in this game. He thought he could change the
character of the position with} Nxc5 $4 24. dxc5 d4 {[%csl Re3] which proved
to be a tactical blunder on the account of} 25. Bg4 $1 Rcd8 26. Rb7 {[%csl Rc7]
} Bb8 27. Bh5 {[%csl Rf7] 1-0 Yu,Y (2723)-Lin,C (2460)/Xinghua 2015/CBM 167} *

