{which is also a novelty.} ({Both} 14. Nxc6 Qh4 15. Rh2 Ndf6 $132 {[%cal Gh7h5]
}) ({and} 14. Nxd7 Qh4 $1 15. Rh2 Kxd7 16. Kf1 h5 $1 $132 {[%csl Ge4] as in 1/
2 (84) Giri,A (2730)-McShane,L (2713) Germany 2013 (84) are too messy and give
black good counter-chances.}) 14... hxg6 15. Kf1 $1 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gc3e1] As you
have probably already gathered by now, this move comes in handy in many
positions in this variation.} Nxc3 ({One of the main points is that} 15... Qh4
{can be strongly answered with} 16. Be1 $16 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gf2f3,Gf1g2]}) (
15... Qf6 {on the other hand, threatens not only the checkmate on f2, but also
Ng3+, so white needs to play} 16. Bf3 {which gives him a slightly more
pleasant position. For instance,} bxc4 17. bxc4 Ng5 18. Bg2 Ne4 19. Bxe4 dxe4
20. Kg2 $14) 16. Rxc3 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gc3c7] Even after exchanging a bunch of
light pieces white still has slightly better prospects, mostly due to control
over the c-file.} Qa5 ({If black tries to close down the c-file with} 16...
dxc4 17. bxc4 b4 {he would give white the advantage in the center and open the
diagonal for his bishop.} 18. Rd3 $14 {[%csl Gc4,Rc6,Gd4][%cal Ge2f3]}) ({The
Stonewall strategy} 16... f5 {[%cal Gd7f6,Gf6e4] is generally a good idea, but
here white gets his foot in the door first with} 17. cxd5 cxd5 18. Rc6 {[%csl
Gc6]} Kf7 19. Kg2 $36 {The rook is very annoying on c6.}) 17. Rc2 dxc4 ({If
black tries to fight for the c-file with} 17... O-O 18. Kg2 Rfc8 {white can
switch his attention to the kingside:} 19. h4 $1 $40 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gh4h5]})
18. bxc4 Nb6 {This is a usual maneuvre that black uses to gain some footing on
the queenside. Here white can steer the game towards a more pleasant endgame
with} 19. Kg2 bxc4 20. Qe1 $5 Qxe1 21. Rxe1 Kd7 22. Rec1 $14 {[%csl Rc6]
though, of course, this is not forced and various other possiblities exist for
both sides. In general, the position after 14.Nxg6 should favor white.} *

