1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. e3 b5 6. b3 Bg4 7. Be2 e6 8. h3 Bh5
9. g4 Bg6 10. Ne5 Nfd7 {This move forces white to swap his knight for bishop,
thus avoiding possible complications with h4-h5.} 11. Nxg6 hxg6 {[%csl Rb8,Gc1,
Rc6,Rd7,Re1,Ge2,Rh4][%cal Gh8h3] We have a fairly typical position for the
Slav defense. White has a bishop pair, but his kingside is a bit exposed after
pushing g4 and it is not clear where his king should seek shelter. The
exchange on g6 also opened the h-file for black rook and solidified black's
kingside to some degree. On the other hand, black has nothing to brag about on
the queenside, where his pieces are a bit clumsy and pawn structure may become
vulnerable. Overall, the position is complex and both sides need to play
accurately.} 12. Qc2 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gc1d2,Ye1c1,Ye1g1] This is the most common
and most flexible move. White still has time to decide where he will deploy
his dark-squared bishop, while Qc2 makes space for 0-0-0, if needed.} ({The
following game saw} 12. Bb2 Bd6 13. Qc2 {which was slightly different compared
to our main line. I give the entire game for instructive purposes:} Nf6 {This
move is sometimes preceded} ({by} 13... g5 {[%cal Gd7f6,Rg4g5] to avoid g4-g5.}
) 14. g5 Ng8 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gg8e7,Ge7f5]} 15. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5]} Nd7 16. c5
Bc7 17. f4 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Re6e5]} Ne7 18. Kf2 Nf5 19. h5 gxh5 20. Bxh5 g6 21.
Bf3 $16 {[%cal Gh1h8] and we get a typical position where white is trying to
break through the tough Slav blockade. After a long maneuvering, the critical
